<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-080-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 080 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Jan 15 1990 v218 n3 p46(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Power problems in the fiber loop. (providing power to fiber opticlocal loops) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Becker, Dustin J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The move toward fiber technology in the local loop createsdifficulty in maintaining consistent transmission.andP;  Standardcopper lines provide metal-to-metal contact; fiber insulates theend of the transmission line.andP;  Three architectures that providetransmission power in a fiber system are detailed: the firstarchitecture uses copper wire extended, or 'dragged,' along withthe fiber, allowing standard power to be provided; the secondarchitecture, known as fiber to the curb, stops the fiber justshort of the subscriber, terminating in an optical interface, withservice distributed over coaxial and copper service drops; and thethird architecture extends fiber all the way to the subscriber andrequires a power source for subscriber equipment.andP;  Various issuesremain to be resolved before fiber optics take over the localloop, including cost-effective architectures, ownership issues,battery technology, access for maintenance, and reliability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTelecommunication systemsTelephone systemsCables.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Power provisioning via &quot;dragged&quot; copper. (chart)Power backfed to pedestal. (chart)Fiber to the home. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>